    <fr:p>By duality, it suffices to prove the first claim.
      We can also suppose <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X_\eta ]]></fr:tex> to be simple.
      We will show that <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[X]]></fr:tex> satisfies one of the conditions of (c) in <fr:ref
addr="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11"
href="hodge-theory-ii-4.4.11.xml"
taxon="Proposition"
number="4.4.11" />.</fr:p>

    <fr:p>Set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[H=\mathbb {M}_c(D)]]></fr:tex>, with <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D]]></fr:tex> a skew field of rank <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[b^2]]></fr:tex> over its centre <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[Z]]></fr:tex>, which we know to be either completely real or completely imaginary.
      If we set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[a=[Z:\mathbb {Q}]]]></fr:tex>, then we have

